In contrast to the bridged-thiolate cleavage yielding the neutral {Fe(NO)2}9, [(SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)(Im)Fe(NO)2] (Im = imidazole), by addition of 2 equiv of imidazole to complex 1 observed in the previous study, the addition of the stronger σ-donating and π-accepting PPh3 ligand triggered the reductive elimination of bridged thiolates of complex 1 to yield the neutral {Fe(NO)2}10, [(PPh3)2Fe(NO)2]. These results unambiguously illustrate one aspect of how the nucleophile L (L = imidazole, PPh3, [OPh]-) functions to control the reaction pathways (bridged-thiolate cleavage, reductive elimination, and deprotonation) upon the reaction of complex 1 and the nucleophile L. Introduction

Dinitrosyl iron complexes (DNICs) have been known to be one of two possible forms for storage and transport of NO in biological systems. Formation of dinitrosyl iron complexes (DNICs) and dinuclear [Fe(μ-SR)(NO)2]2 (Roussin's red ester) by nitrosylation of iron-sulfur cluster-containing proteins in mitochondria and reactions of nitric oxide with thiol-rich proteins in the presence of free iron have been intensely studied. Characterization of both protein-bound and low-molecular weight DNICs (LMW-DNICs) in vitro has been made possible via their distinctive EPR signals at g = 2.03. Although cysteine and  glutathione have been proposed to be the major thiol components of cellular DNICs in vivo, three different kinds of potential coordinated ligands (thiolate, amine, and alkoxide) in DNICs were found and proposed in enzymology (Table ). In particular, the protein-bound DNICs have been well characterized by X-ray crystallography through interaction of human glutathione transferase P1-1 and dinitrosyl diglutathionyl iron complex in vitro/in vivo. Also, amine-coordinated DNICs are found as the intermediate of albumin, Fur-Fe, and iron-quinone complexes via nitrosylation.

elements.content: Recently, we have shown that the facile transformation of the neutral {Fe(NO)2}10, [(sparteine)Fe(NO)2], to the anionic {Fe(NO)2}9, [(S(CH2)3S)Fe(NO)2]-, may occur via the cationic {Fe(NO)2}9, [(sparteine)Fe(NO)2]+. Here, the complex [(sparteine)Fe(NO)2]+ acts as an {Fe(NO)2}-donor reagent in the presence of [S(CH2)3S]2-. The transformation of Roussin's red ester [Fe(μ-SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)(NO)2]2 into the neutral {Fe(NO)2}9, [(SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)(Im)Fe(NO)2] (Im = imidazole), was demonstrated by reaction of [Fe(μ-SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)(NO)2]2 with imidazole. Ligand-replacement between the neutral {Fe(NO)2}9, [(SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)(Im)Fe(NO)2], and the thiolate [SC6H4-o-NHCOPh]- led to the formation of the anionic {Fe(NO)2}9, [(SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)2Fe(NO)2]-. In the study of dinuclear DNICs, the diamagnetic dinuclear iron−thiolate complex [(ON)Fe(S,S-C6H4)2Fe(NO)2]- containing a {Fe(NO)2}9 dinitrosyl iron motif stabilized by {Fe(NO)}7−{Fe(NO)2}9 coupling was synthesized and characterized. The objective of this study was to delineate the synthesis and reactivity of the EPR-active, anionic {Fe(NO)2}9, [(SC6H4-o-NCOPh)Fe(NO)2]- (3), [(SC6H4-o-COO)Fe(NO)2]- (4), and [(N3)2Fe(NO)2]- (7), containing a wide range of S/N/O ligation and the EPR-active, dimeric {Fe(NO)2}9−{Fe(NO)2}9 DNICs [Fe(μ-SC7H4SN)(NO)2]2 (6). Specifically, the transformation of Roussin's red esters (RREs) [Fe(μ-SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)(NO)2]2 (1) and [Fe(μ-SC6H4-o-COOH)(NO)2]2 (2) into (i) the neutral {Fe(NO)2}10, [(PPh3)2Fe(NO)2], via reductive elimination of the bridged thiolates, and (ii) the anionic {Fe(NO)2}9 DNICs 3 and 4 incorporating anionic sulfur−amide and sulfur−carboxylate chelates, respectively, controlled by the nucleophile L (L = PPh3, [OPh]-), were elucidated through reaction of Roussin's red esters 1 and 2 with the nucleophile L.

Complexes 1 and 2 exhibited diagnostic IR νNO stretching frequencies at 1758 s, 1786 s, 1816 vw, and 1756 s, 1782 s, 1812 vw cm-1 (THF), respectively. Results and Discussion

As has been known, reaction of diaryl disulfides (RS)2 (R = C6H4-o-NHCOPh, C6H4-o-COOH) (0.1 mmol) and Fe(CO)2(NO)2 (0.2 mmol)9,10 in tetrahydrofuran (THF) at ambient temperature yielded Roussin's red esters [Fe(μ-SR)(NO)2]2 (R = C6H4-o-NHCOPh (1), C6H4-o-COOH (2)) isolated as a brown-green solid (Scheme a). Complexes 1 and 2 exhibited diagnostic IR νNO stretching frequencies at 1758 s, 1786 s, 1816 vw, and 1756 s, 1782 s, 1812 vw cm-1 (THF), respectively. Consistent with other Roussin's red esters, complexes 1 and 2 were best described as the dimeric dinitrosyl iron complexes with {Fe(NO)2}9-{Fe(NO)2}9 coupling. Both Fe centers (S = 1/2) magnetically  couple to each other via the mediation of thiolate bridges, which rationalizes the absence of paramagnetism and the EPR signal.

As presented in Scheme b, upon addition of 2 equiv of [OPh]- into a THF solution of complex 1 at ambient temperature, instead of the formation of the anionic {Fe(NO)2}9, [(OPh)(SC6H4-o-NHCOPh)Fe(NO)2]-, via splitting of the thiolate bridges, a reaction ensued over the course of 5 min to yield the dark-purple [(SC6H4-o-NCOPh)Fe(NO)2]- (3) with the dianionic [SC6H4-o-NCOPh]2- ligand bound to the {Fe(NO)2} core in a bidentate manner (S,N-bonded) identified by single-crystal X-ray diffraction. The shift in IR ν(NO) from 1758 s, 1786 s, 1816 vw cm-1 (complex 1) to 1690 s, 1737 s cm-1 (THF) is in accordance with the formation of the anionic {Fe(NO)2}9 DNIC 3 (yield 63%). The EPR spectrum of complex 3 exhibits an isotropic signal with g = 2.034 at 298 K and a rhombic signal with g 1 = 2.052, g 2 = 2.033, and g 3 = 2.011 at 77 K (Figure a), the characteristic g value of the {Fe(NO)2}9 DNICs. In contrast to the bridged-thiolate cleavage observed in the reaction of complex 1 and imidazole, the formation process was best assigned to the deprotonation of the bridged-thiolate [SC6H4-o-NHCOPh] of complex 1, and the subsequent chelation of the dianionic ligand [SC6H4-o-NCOPh]2- leading to the formation of complex 3. The surprisingly stable complex 3 is the first example of the anionic {Fe(NO)2}9 DNICs containing the chelating 2-thiolatophenylamido (S,N-coordinated) coordinated to the {Fe(NO)2}9 motif isolated and characterized by single-crystal X-ray diffraction.

We noticed that the IR spectra for the neutral complexes 1 and 2 and the neutral dimeric DNIC 6 had the different pattern and position (1816 vw, 1786 s, 1758 s for 1 vs 1789 s, 1736 s cm-1 (THF) for 6) and separation of NO stretching frequencies (ΔνNO = 28 cm-1 for 1 vs 53 cm-1 for 6). Surprisingly, the formation of complex 5 was not observed upon addition of 2 equiv of PPh3 to the THF solution of complex 6. elements.content: Crystallography. Crystallographic data and structure refinements parameters of complexes 2, 3, 6, and 7 are summarized in the Supporting Information. The crystals chosen for X-ray diffraction studies measured 0.40 × 0.25 × 0.25 mm3 for complex 2, 0.27 × 0.25 × 0.20 mm3 for complex 3, 0.30 × 0.20 × 0.05 mm3 for complex 6, and 0.25 × 0.25 × 0.20 mm3 for complex 7, respectively. Each crystal was mounted on a glass fiber and quickly coated in epoxy resin. Unit-cell parameters were obtained by least-squares refinement. Diffraction measurements for complexes 2, 3, 6, and 7 were carried out on a SMART Apex CCD diffractometer with graphite-monochromated Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.7107 Å) and between 2.24° and 27.50° for complex 2, between 1.42° and 27.50° for complex 3, between 2.51° and 28.33° for complex 6, and between 1.94° and 27.49° for complex 7. Preparation of [Fe(μ-SC 6 H 4 - o -NHC(O)Ph)(NO) 2 ] 2 (1). The THF solution (5 mL) of Fe(CO)2(NO)2 (0.4 mmol) freshly prepared was added to the THF (4 mL) solution of bis(o-benzamidophenyl) disulfide (0.2 mmol, 0.091 g) by cannula under a positive N2 pressure at 0 °C. The resulting solution was stirred at ambient temperature overnight. The solution was filtered through Celite, and hexane was then added to precipitate the brown-green solid [Fe(μ-SC6H4-o-NHC(O)Ph)(NO)2]2 (1) (yield 0.124 g, 90%) characterized by 1H NMR, IR, and UV−vis spectra. IR νNO:  1758 s, 1786 s, 1816 vw (THF) cm-1. Absorption spectrum (CH2Cl2) [λmax, nm (ε, M-1 cm-1)]:  373 (6152), 438 (6104), 780 (120). 1H NMR (CD2Cl2):  δ 9.04 (br), 8.98 (br) (N−H), 8.45−6.55 (m) (S, N−C6H4, −C6H5) ppm.

Preparation of [Fe(μ-SC 6 H 4 - o -COOH)(NO) 2 ] 2 (2). Compound 2,2‘-dithiodibenzoic acid (0.2 mmol, 0.061 g) was dissolved in THF (4 mL) in the 25 mL Schlenk flask, and THF solution (5 mL) of Fe(CO)2(NO)2 (0.4 mmol) freshly prepared was added to it by cannula under a positive N2 pressure at 0 °C. The resulting solution was stirred at ambient temperature overnight. Solvent was then removed under vacuum. The crude solid was redissolved in THF and then filtered through Celite. Addition of hexane to the brown filtrate led to the precipitation of brown solid [Fe(μ-SC6H4-o-COOH)(NO)2]2 (2) (yield 0.19 g, 66%) characterized by 1H NMR, IR, and UV−vis spectra. IR νNO:  1756 s, 1782 s, 1812 vw (THF) cm-1. Absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm (ε, M-1 cm-1)]:  387 (12413), 662 (694), 792 (353). 1H NMR (C4D8O):  δ 6.92−8.08 (m) (C6H4), 10.58 (br) (COOH) ppm.

Preparation of [Na-18-crown-6-ether][(NO) 2 Fe(SC 6 H 4 - o -NC(O)Ph)] (3). The THF solution (5 mL) of complex 1 (0.061 g, 0.2 mmol), sodium phenoxide (0.0464 g, 0.4 mmol), and 18-crown-6-ether (0.106 g, 0.4 mmol) was stirred under N2 for 3 h at room temperature. The mixture solution was filtered through Celite, and hexane was then added to precipitate the black-purple solid [Na-18-crown-6-ether][(NO)2Fe(SC6H4-o-NC(O)Ph)] (3) (0.16 g, 63%). X-ray quality crystals were obtained by diffusion of diethyl ether−hexane (1:1 volume ratio) into THF solution of complex 3 at −20 °C for three weeks. IR νNO:  1690 s, 1737 s (THF) cm-1. Absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm (ε, M-1 cm-1)]:  455 (3803), 560 (3415), 667 (1965). Anal. Calcd for C25H33O9SN3FeNa:  C, 47.63; H, 5.28; N, 6.67. Found:  C, 47.51; H, 6.04; N, 6.79.

Preparation of [PPN][(NO) 2 Fe(SC 6 H 4 - o -COO)] (4). The THF solution (5 mL) of complex 2 (0.1112 g, 0.2 mmol) and sodium phenoxide (0.0464 g, 0.4 mmol) was stirred at ambient temperature for 30 min. The resulting solution was then transferred to a 50 mL Schlenk flask containing 0.230 g of [PPN][Cl] (0.4 mmol), and the mixture solution was stirred overnight at ambient temperature. The mixture solution was filtered through Celite to remove NaCl, and solvent was then removed under vacuum to obtain the dark-brown solid [PPN][(NO)2Fe(SC6H4-o-COO)] (4) (0.126 g, 78%). Diffusion of hexane into THF solution of complex 4 at −20 °C for four weeks led to the dark-brown crystals suitable for X-ray crystallography. IR:  1688 s, 1742 s (νNO); 1625 s (νCO) (THF) cm-1. Absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm (ε, M-1 cm-1)]:  426 (1775), 475 (1420), 670 (424), 947 (123). Anal. Calcd for C43H34O4SN3P2Fe:  C, 64.03; H, 4.25; N, 5.21. Found:  C, 63.93; H, 4.50; N, 5.12.

Reaction of [Fe(μ-SC 6 H 4 - o -NHC(O)Ph)(NO) 2 ] 2 (1) and PPh 3 . The THF solution of complex 1 (0.2 mmol), freshly prepared from reaction of [Fe(CO)2(NO)2] (0.4 mmol) and bis(o-benzamidophenyl) disulfide (0.2 mmol, 0.091 g) in THF (5 mL), was transferred to a 50-mL Schlenk flask loaded with PPh3 (0.105 g, 0.8 mmol) by a cannula under positive N2 pressure at ambient temperature. The mixture solution was stirred for 1 h. The solution was then concentrated, and diethyl ether−hexane (5:15 mL) was added to precipitate yellow-brown solid [(PPh3)2Fe(NO)2] (5). The resulting mixture was then filtered to separate the solid and solution. The yellow-brown solid was redissolved in THF, and then diffusion of hexane into the THF solution of complex 5 at −15 °C led to the brown crystals of the known complex 5 (yield 0.236 g, 92%) identified by IR (IR νNO:  1676 s, 1718 s cm-1 (THF)), UV−vis (absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm]:  445, 665), and single-crystal X-ray diffraction. The THF−diethyl ether−hexane filtrate was dried under vacuum to acquire the greenish-yellow solid, and then diethyl ether was added to extract bis(o-benzamidophenyl) disulfide characterized by 1H NMR (1H NMR (CDCl3):  δ 6.92 (t), 7.27 (t), 7.41 (m), 7.53 (t), 7.66 (d), 8.47 (d) (Ph); 8.91 (br) (NH) ppm).

Preparation of [Fe(μ-SC 7 H 4 SN)(NO) 2 ] 2 (6). Bis(2-benzothiozolyl) disulfide (0.033 g, 0.1 mmol) was added into the THF solution of [Fe(CO)2(NO)2], freshly prepared from reaction of [PPN][Fe(CO)3NO] (0.141 g, 0.2 mmol) and [NO][BF4] (0.024 g, 0.2 mmol), and stirred for 30 min under N2 atmosphere at ambient temperature. The reaction was monitored with FTIR. IR spectrum (IR νNO:  1736 s, 1789 s cm-1 (THF)) was assigned to the formation of [Fe(μ-SC7H4SN)(NO)2]2 (6). Diffusion of hexane into the THF solution of complex 6 at −15 °C led to the dark red crystals suitable for single-crystal X-ray diffraction (yield 0.050 g, 89%). IR νNO:  1736 s, 1789 s cm-1 (THF). Absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm (ε, M-1 cm-1)]:  428 (984), 549 (241), 753(55). Anal. Calcd for C14H8N6O4S4Fe:  C, 29.80; H, 1.43; N, 14.90. Found:  C, 30.21; H, 1.55; N, 15.26.

Reaction of [(PPh 3 ) 2 Fe(NO) 2 ] (5) and Bis(2-benzothiozolyl) Disulfide. A THF solution (10 mL) of [(PPh3)2Fe(NO)2] (0.128 g, 0.2 mmol) was transferred to a 50 mL Schlenk flask loaded with bis(2-benzothiozolyl) disulfide (0.033 g 0.1 mmol) by cannula under positive N2 pressure at room temperature. The reaction mixture was stirred for 2 h at room temperature. The solution was concentrated under vacuum, and hexane was added to precipitate the dark-red solid assigned to the formation of complex 6 (yield 0.047 g, 83%) characterized by IR (IR νNO:  1736 s, 1789 s cm-1 (THF)), and UV−vis (absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm]:  428, 549, 753).

Reaction of [Fe(μ-SC 7 H 4 SN-)(NO) 2 ] 2 (6) and [PPN][SC 7 H 4 SN]. Complex 6 (0.113 g, 0.2 mmol) and [PPN][SC7H4SN] (0.282 g, 0.4 mmol) were dissolved in THF (20 mL) under N2 atmosphere. The reaction mixture was stirred at room temperature for 1 h, and then diethyl ether was added to precipitate the dark-red solid [PPN][(SC7H4SN)2Fe(NO)2] (8) (yield 0.371 g, 94%) characterized by IR (IR νNO:  1716 s, 1766 s cm-1 (THF)), and UV−vis (absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm]:  465, 799 nm).

Preparation of [PPN][(N 3 ) 2 Fe(NO) 2 ] (7). Complex 6 (0.0524 g, 0.1 mmol) and [PPN][N3] (0.232 g, 0.4 mmol) were dissolved in THF (20 mL) under N2 atmosphere. The reaction mixture was stirred at room temperature overnight, and the resulting solution was filtered through Celite to separate the insoluble solid. The reaction solution was monitored with FTIR. IR spectrum (νNO:  1698 s, 1755 s cm-1 (THF)) was assigned to the formation of [PPN][(N3)2Fe(NO)2] (7). Diffusion of hexane into the THF solution of complex 7 at −15 °C led to the red-brown crystals suitable for single-crystal X-ray diffraction (yield 0.129 g, 87%). IR νNO:  1698 s, 1755 s cm-1 (THF). Absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm (ε, M-1 cm-1)]:  397 (6163), 502 (829), 701 (356). Anal. Calcd for C36H30N9P2O2Fe:  C, 58.55; H, 4.09; N, 17.07. Found:  C, 58.18; H, 4.73; N, 16.91.

Reaction of [PPN][(SC 7 H 4 SN) 2 Fe(NO) 2 ] and [PPN][N 3 ]. A THF solution (15 mL) of complex 8 (0.392 g, 0.4 mmol) was transferred to a 50 mL Schlenk flask loaded with [PPN][N3] (0.464 g, 0.8 mmol) by a cannula under positive N2 pressure at room temperature. The reaction solution was stirred overnight at room temperature, and the resulting mixture was filtered through Celite to separate the insoluble solid. The solution was then concentrated under vacuum, and diethyl ether−hexane (15:15 mL) was added to precipitate the red-brown solid complex 7 (yield 0.230 g, 78%) characterized by IR (IR νNO:  1698 s, 1755 s cm-1 (THF)) and UV−vis (absorption spectrum (THF) [λmax, nm (ε, M-1 cm-1)]:  397, 502, 701 nm).
